ng OGNL build includes JVM args because they were added manually. For the Java-run fix generation, it would be helpful if the setup notified the agent to preserve or add these JVM args. Also, I’m wondering if JDK 25 will handle `--illegal-access` differently since it was removed in JDK 17.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering JDK argument changes**\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out the status of the `--illegal-access=permit` option in different JDK versions. In JDK 17, it seems this option was removed but still accepted with a warning stating it's being ignored. But for JDK 25, it might not even be recognized. It seems prudent not to advise using `--illegal-access`, as it could lead to confusion or errors if it’s completely unsupported in future versions. Overall, keeping up with these changes is important!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating JVM Arguments**\\n\\nI’m considering whether JVM arguments qualify as environment or system properties. The test-code setup guidelines suggest modifications like `--add-opens` for specific packages. It looks like I should avoid global properties like `ognl.security.manager` and only apply them to scoped tests. The question implies that no global setup is necessary. Still, if there's a sandbox path, we should manage the security manager there. I'll note there's a transitive dependency that doesn't require extra setup. The potential risk from future JDK changes is something to keep in mind.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering JSON Format**\\n\\nI'm pondering whether `--illegal-access` should be avoided. It seems I need to ensure the JSON output is valid and doesn't include any markdown. The final output should be strictly in JSON format without any other annotations or styles. Keeping it clean and compliant is essential, so I’ll focus on making sure everything sticks to a proper JSON structure. There’s no room for errors in formatting here!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"advisory_preparation\",\n  \"summary\": \"OGNL is an in-memory expression/reflection library with only a transitive javassist runtime dependency, but its own JDK17+ test profile requires module opens for reflective coverage.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"Configure generated JVM tests with module opens when exercising OGNL reflection internals: --add-opens=java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED and, for collection/JDK-internal accessor coverage, --add-opens=java.base/java.util=ALL-UNNAMED. No Docker image, extra Maven dependency, environment variable, or global system property is required. Do not set ognl.security.manager globally; if testing that mode, set and restore it inside the individual test.\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"JDK 25 SecurityManager removal/deprecation behavior may make existing security-manager-focused tests fail independently of setup.\",\n    \"org.javassist:javassist:3.29.0-GA is already a transitive runtime dependency of ognl:ognl:3.3.5, so adding it explicitly would likely be redundant unless Gradle resolution proves otherwise.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0ec1acbd525f801f016a422561ef048197a9f8c525044a52a4\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2446, "output": 1290, "cacheRead": 38400, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 42136, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1782719822092, "responseId": "resp_0ec1acbd525f801f016a42254e8fe48197b009542ca3340c22"}, "toolResults": []}
